        So can someone tell me how many individual streams per song it takes to reach number 100 on the official chart?

        The reason I ask is because then someone has the terrible complicated mathematical task of working out how many streams is needed for number 99, and 98, and so on and so on.

        Surely it was easier in the days of physical sales?

        My argument is in the days of physical sales, music had to be current, because it was down to what the record company released as singles, invariably new material

        But with streaming technically anything obscure could become a hit single, even an album track from the 70's could be number 1 if enough people streamed it.

        But how is that bringing on new talent compared to how the industry was?

        I remember when downloading mp3's became legal and to be allowed into influencing the charts and thinking omg this is a mistake, but it ruduced piracy as illegal file sharing dropped off as it was cheap to download a whole album or individual tracks and put them on an mp3 player.

        But who would ever think for a cheap subscription we could have access to the world's library of music via apps like Spotify, Deezer?

        More than we ever need if we only care to admit it. To me surely its better to concentrate on the artists we love to listen to and support them, a bit like a football fan supports their team right? Why are we watering everything down to an industry that frezzes out other potential?

        Yet the chart system currently has catered everything around for the teenager, but why are we doing that?
